  "text": "When we ask someone with an accent what society he or she comes from, the person might say, \"China,\" \"Argentina,\" or \"Here, the United States.\" In everyday language, we tend to use the word society to refer to nations. However, Durkheim means something different by the concept of society. He uses the term to refer to any form of ongoing and patterned interactions in groups: \"Every aggregate of individuals who are in continuous contact form a society\" (Durkheim, 1893 [CITATION_1] .",
